
[1]stoic

   STOIC, n. [Gr., a porch in Athens where the philosopher Zeno taught.] A
   disciple of the philosopher Zeno, who founded a sect. He taught that
   men should be free from passion, unmoved by joy or grief, and submit
   without complaint to the unavoidable necessity by which all things are
   governed.
